outh Dalton, Yorkshire, England":"South Dalton, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"About 1480–1554":"about 1480–1554","1464–1539":"1464–1539","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1475–1487":"1475–1487","1480–1554":"1480–1554","1490–1554":"1490–1554","–1559":"–1559","1480–1504":"1480–1504","1528–1558":"1528–1558","1450–1524":"1450–1524","–Female":"Deceased","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","About 1480":"about 1480","1524":"1524","1554":"1554","1487":"1487","1475":"1475","1530":"1530","1464":"1464","1528":"1528","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","1559":"1559","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","South Dalton, Yorkshire, England":"South Dalton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gover","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>go(e)</i> + <i>faire</i> ‘beautifully; gently, quietly’.","English: alternatively, a variant of   Govier  , which is unexplained.","Altered form of French   Gauvreau  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Govier","meanings":["English (southwestern): unexplained."]}]},{"name":"Margeret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margeret Gover was born about 1480, in Surrey, England as the daughter of Thomas Gower van Sittenham and Agnes Thwaites. She had at least 1 daughter with William Aislaby. She died in 1554, in South Dalton, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"About 1480–1554":"umbes 1480–1554","1464–1539":"1464–1539","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1475–1487":"1475–1487","1480–1554":"1480–1554","1490–1554":"1490–1554","–1559":"–1559","1480–1504":"1480–1504","1528–1558":"1528–1558","1450–1524":"1450–1524","–Female":"Surnud","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","About 1480":"umbes 1480","1524":"1524","1554":"1554","1487":"1487","1475":"1475","1530":"1530","1464":"1464","1528":"1528","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","1559":"1559","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","South Dalton, Yorksh